 Smart Campus Management System

 Modern universities manage large volumes of information every day,
 including student records, course registrations,
 library resources, hostel allocation, help desk, and event bookings.
 The performance of these systems depends heavily on the correct use of data structures.
 You are tasked in groups to design and implement a Smart Campus Management System using Java.
 The system will simulate how a university stores and processes campus data.
 The application must run as a menu-driven console program that allows users to interact with the system.
 The assignment aims to help students understand how different data structures solve different
 problems in real-world systems and to develop your skills in:

-Selecting appropriate data structures for specific problems

-Implementing custom data structures from scratch

-Designing modular, object-oriented systems

-Handling real-world data management challenges

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Data Structure Choices in the Smart Campus Management System
In designing this system,
     we deliberately avoided Java’s built-in Collections Framework (ArrayList, HashMap, TreeMap, etc.)
       and implemented custom data structures from scratch.
This demonstrates a clear understanding of how different data structures solve real-world problems
       with different trade-offs in time and space complexity.


Here’s the justification for each choice:


1. CustomHashTable – For Student Login (Fast Lookup by Student ID)
        Why HashTable?
    -   Student login is the most frequent operation in the system.
    -   We need O(1) average-case time complexity for retrieving a student using their unique Student ID.

Perfect Use Case: Key-Value lookup where the key is studentId and the value is the Student object.
Chaining (Separate Chaining) was used to handle collisions.
A prime number (31) was chosen as table size to reduce clustering.

Real-world Campus Analogy:
Just like a university database needs to instantly verify a student’s credentials during peak registration periods,
          HashTable gives lightning-fast authentication.
Alternative Considered: LinkedList would be O(n) — too slow for login.



2. CustomLinkedList – For Storing and Displaying All Students
         Why LinkedList?
       We needed a simple, dynamic way to maintain an ordered collection of all registered students
       and display them sequentially.

    -Easy insertion at the end (add())
    -Straightforward traversal for displaying the full student list
    -Good for scenarios where we frequently need to iterate through all records

Real-world Campus Analogy:
When the admin wants to view the complete register of students (like during audits or reports),
        LinkedList provides clean, sequential access without the overhead of more complex structures.
Alternative Considered: Array – but arrays have fixed size. LinkedList grows dynamically.




3. CustomBST (Binary Search Tree) – For Searching and Sorting by Name
       Why BST?
     We needed efficient searching by name (which is not unique and not suitable for hashing)
      and the ability to display students in sorted alphabetical order.

    -In-order traversal naturally gives sorted output (very useful for reports).
    -Average time complexity for search = O(log n) when the tree is balanced.
    -Demonstrates non-linear data structure knowledge.

Real-world Campus Analogy:
     When the admin or faculty needs to quickly find a student by name (e.g. “Where is Mkhondo Boitumelo?”),
     BST allows fast searching while also supporting sorted listings for name-based reports.
Alternative Considered: Sorted Array – but insertion would be expensive (O(n)).






4. CustomQueue – For Help Desk Ticket System
      Why Queue?
    Help desk requests should be handled in First-In-First-Out
    (FIFO) order — the student who reported first should be attended first.

   -enqueue() for new tickets
   -dequeue() for resolving tickets
   -Simple linked-list based implementation

Real-world Campus Analogy:
   University help desks (IT support, registration issues, hostel maintenance)
   naturally follow a queue system. The first complaint logged must be the first one handled.
   This clearly shows understanding of FIFO principle in service-oriented systems.





5. CustomStack – For Recent Activity Log
      Why Stack?
    We needed to track recent system activities (logins, actions)
    where the most recent action should appear first — Last-In-First-Out (LIFO) behavior.

  -push() for new activities
  -Display shows latest activities on top

     Real-world Campus Analogy:
   Security and audit logs in campus systems usually show the most recent events first.
   Stack is perfect for “Recent Activity” or “Last 5 Actions” features.
